bug.short_desc: Disconnect and reconnecting my DVI kills video

long_desc.thetext:
Dear Red Hat,,
FC 23 and FC24 Beta, X64 Fedora-Live-Xfce-x86_64-23-10.iso Fedora-Xfce-Live-x86_64-24_Beta-1.4.iso
Oh now this is a real pain in the neck (not my "exact" word).
On my Supermicro C7Z87 motherboard with on processor video (i3-4130),
https://www.supermicro.com/products/motherboard/Core/Z87/C7Z87.cfm http://ark.intel.com/products/77480/Intel-Core-i3-4130-Processor-3M-Cache-3_40-GHz http://www.intel.com/content/www/us/en/support/graphics-drivers/intel-hd-graphics-4400-for-4th-generation-intel-core-processors.html
after one of my FC23 updates, if I disconnect my DVI connector and reconnect it, either manually or with a KVM switch
IOGEAR Network GCS922U 2Port USB DVI Cable KVM Switch https://www.iogear.com/support/dm/manual/GCS922U
I completely lose my video. Screen is completely blank.
But <ctrl><alt><f2> works and I can do whatever I want in command line mode, including restarting the computer, which brings back my video on <ctrl><alt><f1> (the main screen).
Please fix!
Many thanks, -T

My work around. You lose all your open programs, but the display does come back. You do have to log in again
[CODE]kill -HUP $(ps ax | grep [x]org | awk '{print $1}')[/CODE]
Does this help in the troubleshooting?

Hi,
(In reply to Todd from comment #1) > My work around. You lose all your open programs, but the display does come > back. You do have to log in again > > [CODE]kill -HUP $(ps ax | grep [x]org | awk '{print $1}')[/CODE] > > Does this help in the troubleshooting?
Yes it does, this sounds like the replugging of the dvi does not generate a hotplug event. Can you try simply running "xrandr" and if that does not help "xrandr --auto" from a terminal under X when you've the problem?
Regards,
Hans

Hi,
So xrandr does see your monitor after the unplug / replug it just does not have a mode assigned.
Did you try:
xrandr -d :0.0 --auto
?
Also can you try running:
xrandr -d :0.0 --output HDMI3 --mode 1280x1024
And see if that fixes things ?
What desktop environment are you running ?
Regards,
Hans

I came up with an interesting work around.
Before switching to a different computer (KVM switch), I press <ctrl><alt><f2> and open my user account at the command line. Then I switch to the other computer. When I want to go back, I switch, get the command line for f2, then press <ctrl><alt><f1> and I am back to my GUI.
I am extremely pleased to report this this is no longer an issue under Fedora Core 25. Thank you!
